## Theory

### Introduction to VHDL

VHDL (VHSIC Hardware Description Language) is a hardware description language used to model and design digital systems such as logic gates, combinational circuits, sequential circuits, and processors. It allows designers to describe hardware behavior before actual implementation.

### Open-Source Simulation Environment

An open-source simulation environment provides tools for writing, compiling, simulating, and testing VHDL programs. A commonly used open-source VHDL simulator is **GHDL**, which supports VHDL standards and enables verification of digital circuit designs.


## Structure of a VHDL Program

A VHDL program generally consists of:

### 1. Library Declaration

Libraries contain predefined functions and data types.

```vhdl
library IEEE;
use IEEE.STD_LOGIC_1164.ALL;
```

### 2. Entity Declaration

Defines the input and output ports of the circuit.

```vhdl
entity AND_GATE is
Port (
    A : in STD_LOGIC;
    B : in STD_LOGIC;
    Y : out STD_LOGIC
);
end AND_GATE;
```

### 3. Architecture Body

Describes the behavior of the circuit.

```vhdl
architecture Behavioral of AND_GATE is
begin
    Y <= A and B;
end Behavioral;
```

